<p class="MsoNormal" align="center" style="text-align:center"><b><u>
<span lang="EN-US">10 Things You Need to Know About Selling Your Telecom 
Accounts</span></u></b></p>
<p class="midgray_normal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="1">
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Know your buyer</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">You 
		business is like a child that you have nurtured and cared for over the 
		years. It represents untold hours of your life invested in a labor of 
		love. It may be hard to imagine life without it. If it is successful, 
		you have high expectations for its value. If it is not successful, you 
		may be ready to be rid of it for any reasonable offer. Either way, not 
		only does it represent some portion of your wealth, but it also 
		represents your reputation. Your investors, business partners, agents, 
		employees, vendors, bankers, and most importantly of all, your 
		customers, all hold you accountable and responsible to be a good 
		steward. Selecting a buyer is a critical decision. You only want to do 
		this once and you want to do it right.</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">It 
		has been said that reputation is what others think of us. Character is 
		what we know ourselves to be. Long-term relationships are usually based 
		on strength of character. Persons of like character tend to bond 
		together because they see in one another a common set of virtues and 
		values. In business, people are often forced to deal successfully with 
		people of questionable character. But when it comes to the very personal 
		and individual decision to sell your business, you want not only to have 
		the protection of laws and iron-clad contracts, but you also want to 
		trust the character of the other party. Legal remedies to disputes are a 
		tedious, expensive and generally to be avoided. In difficult situations, 
		character rises to the surface.</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">Be 
		prepared to defend your choice of buyers in the event that something 
		goes wrong. </span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">The cascading bankruptcy</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Talk to any RBOC, and they can describe an altogether too common 
		occurrence in Telecom, the cascading bankruptcy. Telecom accounts are 
		converted in mass from one failed OCN to another, only to find that the 
		new OCN progresses into yet another failure. There are stories of 
		unscrupulous individuals abandoning large debts, and slipping off into 
		the night, only to be back in business the next day under a new OCN, 
		with the same accounts. The RBOCs chase these debts through legal 
		nightmares, trying to collect what is owed to them. Imagine if you 
		blundered into a deal with one of these crooks, how would you be able to 
		protect yourself? Would you find yourself in a long line of unsatisfied 
		creditors, many of whom have extensive legal resources at their command?</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">The litigious individual</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">You 
		don’t have to be in business very long before you will meet or know 
		individuals and companies that make their way in life by being 
		litigious. They draw their lawyers like a gun. They have a history of 
		lawsuits. They are quick to threaten legal action rather than resolve 
		issues amicably. They seldom live within the four corners of their 
		agreements and they manipulate the system to their advantage. They use 
		the cost and time involved in legal battles to try to coerce people into 
		accepting settlements that they would otherwise never agree to. Avoid 
		dealing with them. In any deal, there may evolve issues that require 
		resolution between the parties.</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Experience counts</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Like most of life, there is a right way and wrong way to do things. Many 
		of these lessons are best learned in the school of hard knocks. Every 
		merger and acquisition teaches lessons about best practices. Neither the 
		buyer nor the seller benefit from the mistakes that can be avoided with 
		the proper knowledge. Each deal is unique and decisions have to be made 
		about methods and processes. You want to deal with business partners who 
		are competent, capable and experienced. You need a buyer who is flexible 
		and adaptable, but who has the integrity to refuse a deal rather than 
		agree to something that won’t work for both parties. Find out how many 
		mergers and acquisitions prospective buyers have gone through. More 
		specifically, find out if they are experienced in buying Telecom 
		accounts. Do they have tried and true approaches that have been proven 
		to work? Are they savvy enough to ask the right questions and garner the 
		information needed to sculpt a deal that works for everyone affected?</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Footprint</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">As 
		you know, Telecom can vary significantly by Region, by State, by Zone, 
		by dominant ILEC, by CLEC and by product. &nbsp;Is the buyer licensed in your 
		geographic footprint? If not, is the buyer purchasing your licenses? 
		Does the buyer understand the deposit and bonding requirements? Does the 
		buyer understand the regulatory requirements imposed by the FCC and by 
		the various States? Does your buyer currently serve customers in your 
		same geographic footprint? Does your buyer understand the differences as 
		you move from one GEO code to the next? Does the buyer have 
		interconnection agreements and local wholesale agreements in place with 
		all of your underlying ILECs? If not, is the buyer assuming your 
		agreements? Will the buyer take over your OCN and retain your existing 
		Billing Account Numbers? &nbsp;Will the underlying vendors approve those 
		assumptions? Is the buyer going to service all of the accounts you are 
		selling? Do you have customers that are outside the buyer’s footprint 
		and that the buyer cannot service?</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Slamming</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Simply put, slamming is converting customers from one OCN to another 
		without complying with the regulations governing such conversions. 
		Structuring the transfer of accounts is the science of complying with 
		regulations while making the transfer as painless and transparent as 
		possible for the customers. Regulations impose severe penalties for 
		slamming. Does the buyer have regulatory counsel, and is the buyer aware 
		of these regulations? Does the buyer intend to comply with them? 
		Customer complaints to regulatory authorities may be unavoidable, but 
		should be minimized, and proper protections should be in place for both 
		buyer and seller. Depending upon your situation, it may be vitally 
		important that you are entirely comfortable with how the customers will 
		be converted. You may wish to seek the advice of regulatory counsel.<br>
		<br>
&nbsp;</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Facilities or not?</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Facilities</span></u></b></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
</ol>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>i.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Network - As you know, the knowledge and skill sets required to operate a 
facilities based carrier are much different than a non-facilities based carrier. 
Are you facilities based? What of capacity concerns, either idle capacity or 
inadequate capacity? If so, does the buyer have experience with facilities based 
operations? Does the buyer understand the cost model? Will the buyer need to 
take ownership of your facilities in order to service your customers? Are you 
co-located? Are leased facilities involved? Will the buyer assume those 
relationships? Will the buyer need to retain your Network Engineering 
capabilities and if so, how will that be managed?</span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>ii.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Call Center – Will the buyer retain your call center or will the 
customers be redirected to the buyer’s existing call center? </span></p>
<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="7" type="1">
	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="2" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Non-facilities based</span></u></b></li>
	</ol>
</ol>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>i.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Wholesale versus Resale – The old Unbundled Network Elements Platform 
(“UNEP”), now referred to as Local Wholesale Agreements, has a much different 
cost structure than does resale. What is the mix of your customer base between 
Wholesale and Resale? Will the buyer convert your Wholesale customers to Resale 
or visa versa? </span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; margin-left: 2.0in">
<span lang="EN-US">1.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>If you are Wholesale, does the buyer understand CABS billing? Does the 
buyer have the processes in place to process the DUFs, bill and collect the CABS 
revenue? How significant is CABS revenue to the deal? Is the buyer taking your 
existing CABS receivables?</span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>ii.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Conversion – Until the customers are converted to the buyer’s OCN, they 
remain on your OCN and on your ILEC invoice. Once the customers are converted, 
the buyer will be charged a pro-rate for the partial month, plus a full month’s 
recurring charges, and you will receive a prorated credit. Will the buyer 
convert the customers from your OCN to the buyers OCN? If so, what will be the 
effective date of that conversion? What will trigger the conversion? Is a 
customer payment required? Is a customer LOA required? Is TPV required?</span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>iii.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Pro-Rate – Will there be any pro-ration of customer revenues? If so, are 
the customers pre-paid or post-paid? Who will collect from the customer and how? 
What will be the settlement process?</span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>iv.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Disputed Charges – Do you have a disputes pending with the underlying 
ILECs? If so, what will happen to those disputes after the sale? Will you retain 
them and continue to be charged with collecting those credits? Or will the buyer 
assume those disputes and take over the settlement process with the ILEC? Is the 
buyer experienced in auditing ILEC invoices and in settling ILEC disputes? Have 
those disputes been withheld from payment to the ILEC? Or do those disputes 
represent money you paid to the ILEC and that you were expecting to recover from 
the ILEC? Do the disputes represent an asset or a liability?</span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="margin-left:99.0pt;text-align:justify">
<span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="8" type="1">
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Customers</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Change - Customers hate change. What will be your customers’ experience? 
		How will they be informed? How will it be presented to them? How likely 
		are they to stay? Does the buyer have a plan that will result in a high 
		level of customer retention? There are ways to manage the change that 
		will be more intrusive or less intrusive to the customers.</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Customer Service – Does the buyer have an adequate call center to handle 
		the influx of customers? &nbsp;Will the buyer reach out to the customers to 
		embrace them and answer their questions and concerns?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Customer billing – Will the buyer retain your customer billing process 
		or convert the customers to the buyers billing platform? Will the 
		customers due dates change? Do the customers owe any past due balances? 
		If so, who will collect those? Are any of the customers pre-paid? If so, 
		how will the cutoff be settled?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Prices and Products - Your prices and products were a significant factor 
		in why your customers chose to do business with you. You understand your 
		market. You know your competition. You built your products and services 
		to meet the needs of your customers. Does the buyer offer similar 
		products and services? What does the buyer charge? Will your prices be 
		honored to your customers? Will your customers receive similar products 
		and services from the buyer at similar prices? You should be comfortable 
		with the buyer’s plan regarding prices and products. </span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Unprofitable customers – Do you have products and prices that need to be 
		reviewed and updated in light of subsequent changes in the market? Do 
		you have unprofitable customers and/or customers with less than 
		acceptable margins? Is the buyer savvy enough to identify these 
		customers? What is the buyer’s plan to migrate these customers to 
		profitable products and prices?</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Sales Channels</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Agents</span></u></b></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
</ol>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>i.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Do you use agents? Did the agents sign up the new customers? Do the 
agents collect and process the recurring monthly payments? If so, who truly 
controls the customers? Is it you or is it the agent? If it is the agent, how 
important is it that the buyer retains the agent base? If the agents jump ship, 
will the customers follow? Is the buyer savvy about dealing with agents? Does 
the buyer have a plan to embrace and retain the agents? Does the buyer have the 
network in place to give the agents price and product lookup and to allow the 
agents to process orders, moves, changes, conversions and payments? How quickly 
can the buyer link up with your agents? How does the buyer pay the agents their 
commission? Will the buyer honor your agent agreements? Or will the agents be 
asked to accept significant changes? What will be your agents’ experience?</span></p>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>ii.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Master Agency – Are you willing to assist the buyer with converting the 
agents and retaining the agents? If so, how will you be compensated? Will there 
be an override?</span></p>
<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="9" type="1">
	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="2" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal"><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;<b><u>Direct Sales</u></b></span></li>
	</ol>
</ol>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>i.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Did your customers come to you over the telephone via a 1-800 number? 
Does your marketing and promotion drive the customers to call your call center? 
Do your customers pay over the phone by credit card, debit card and/or check by 
phone? If so, how will the buyer accommodate these customers? Will the buyer 
retain your 800 numbers? What will happen to the new sales leads coming in after 
the sale?</span></p>
<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="9" type="1">
	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="3" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Web Based Sales</span></u></b></li>
	</ol>
</ol>
<p class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -1.5in; margin-left: 1.5in">
<span lang="EN-US"><span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>i.<span style="font:7.0pt &quot;Times New Roman&quot;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Did your customers come to you over the web? Does your marketing and 
advertising drive customers to a web site? Do you have a web page where they 
sign up and make payments? If so, is the buyer web enabled? Will the buyer 
retain your web page? Will the customers be re-directed to the buyer’s web page? 
What is the buyers plan for serving these web savvy customers?</span></p>
<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="10" type="1">
	<li class="midgray_normal"><b><u><span lang="EN-US">Deal structure</span></u></b>
 	<ol style="margin-top: 0in; margin-bottom: 0in" start="1" type="a">
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">NDA 
		– a non-disclosure agreement should be signed by both parties</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Confidential and proprietary information – it is common for certain 
		information to be withheld by the seller until a deal is negotiated. For 
		example, it is customary for a seller to withhold customer name and 
		addresses until the deal closes, although the buyer will likely need to 
		know City, State and Zip. The last 4 digits of customer phone numbers 
		are also commonly withheld, although the buyer will likely need to know 
		NPANXX.</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">Is 
		this an asset sale or are you selling ownership of the business? Is your 
		business a corporation? If so, is it a stock transaction?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		What exactly are you selling? Customer base only? All customers or just 
		selected customers? Are other assets being sold as well? What about 
		trade names and other intangibles? Licenses? Network? Facilities? 
		Equipment? Are you keeping any assets? </span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">Do 
		you plan to continue in business after the sale? Are you giving a 
		non-compete?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">Key 
		Contracts – Who are your key business partners? Who do you do business 
		with? Are leases, vendor contracts, interconnection agreements, software 
		licenses, contractor agreements, agent agreements and other agreements 
		transferable to the buyer? Does the buyer want or need any of them?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Your Services –What are your duties and obligations to the buyer? To 
		what extent will you be involved after the sale?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Ongoing Marketing – Do you plan to continue to market and will you be 
		generating additional customers after the sale? If so, will you need or 
		want to transfer any of those to the buyer? How will you be compensated?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Employees – Does the buyer want or need to hire or retain any of your 
		employees?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Valuation – How will the price be negotiated?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Payment – How much of the price is due at closing? Are you offering 
		seller financing? Will you accept installment payments? Is there any 
		escrow? Is there any earn out if the sale goes better than planned? Are 
		there any terms or conditions that may affect the price after the 
		closing?</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">Due 
		diligence – The buyer will want to do some sort of due diligence. This 
		may involve physical inspections, data base dumps, audits, reviews, site 
		visits, interviews, etc. Be prepared to open up and share.</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Last minute changes – Be wary of changes negotiated at the last minute 
		or substituted for previously agreed upon terms and conditions. More 
		than one deal has blown up because the parties made last minute changes 
		that turned out to be very significant.</span></li>
		<li class="midgray_normal" style="text-align: justify"><span lang="EN-US">
		Agreement – Insure you have complete agreement between buyer and seller 
		on all key terms and conditions before you transfer any assets. Seek the 
		advice of counsel and consider having a lawyer present at closing. Make 
		sure there is no ambiguity. Phrases like “to be negotiated later” or 
		“acceptable to both parties” may be fine provided both parties are 
		comfortable.</span></li>
	</ol>
	</li>
</ol>
